Philippicarum: se. orationum. The name of “Philippics’' (i.e. “concerning Philip'’) was originally applied to certain speeches of the Athenian orator Demosthenes, in which he attached Philip of Macedon, between the years 351-341 B.c. The name was hence trans- ferred to the fourteen speeches in which Cicero more or less directly attacks Antonius, or the policy of Antonius; not so much from any resemblance in tone 01· language‚* as from the siinilarity between the nolitia-al attitudes of the two orators. As Demosthenes represented free Athens strnggling against the encroachments of King Philip, so Cicero represented the free Republie struggling against the threatened military despotism of Antonius.
